## Business Logic

### 1. Service Summary

The Account Management Service provides a comprehensive API for managing user accounts. It allows clients to create, read, update, and delete account information. The service supports account validation through external calls and integrates with messaging systems for event-driven architecture. It utilizes both relational and non-relational databases for data storage, ensuring flexibility and scalability. The service is designed to handle various account types and provides detailed error handling for exceptional scenarios.

### 2. Summary Table

| **Base Path**                | **Source Repository**          | **Description**                                                                                   |
|------------------------------|--------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `/accounts`                  | [GitHub Repo Link](#)         | API for managing user accounts, including creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion of accounts.|
| `/accounts/{id}`             | [GitHub Repo Link](#)         | API for managing specific user account details by ID, allowing retrieval, updating, and deletion. |

### 3. Overall API Specification

| **Endpoint**            | **Method** | **Description**                                           | **Request Body**                           | **Responses**                          | **Authentication** |
|-------------------------|------------|-----------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------|--------------------|
| `/accounts`             | GET        | Retrieve all accounts                                      | N/A                                        | 200 OK - List of accounts              | None               |
| `/accounts`             | POST       | Create a new account                                      | Account object                             | 201 Created - Account created          | None               |
| `/accounts/{id}`        | GET        | Retrieve account by ID                                    | N/A                                        | 200 OK - Account details<br>404 Not Found - Account not found | None               |
| `/accounts/{id}`        | PUT        | Update an existing account                                 | Account object                             | 200 OK - Account updated<br>404 Not Found - Account not found | None               |
| `/accounts/{id}`        | DELETE     | Delete an account by ID                                   | N/A                                        | 204 No Content - Account deleted<br>404 Not Found - Account not found | None               |

### 4. Endpoints Overview

- **GET /accounts**: Retrieves a list of all accounts.
- **POST /accounts**: Creates a new account with the provided details.
- **GET /accounts/{id}**: Gets the details of a specific account by its ID.
- **PUT /accounts/{id}**: Updates the details of an existing account identified by its ID.
- **DELETE /accounts/{id}**: Deletes the account associated with the specified ID.

This structured response provides a detailed summary of the Account Management Service, including its functionality, endpoints, and how to interact with the API.

## Plant UML script

Below is a PlantUML sequence diagram script that captures the business logic and interactions described. This diagram includes all key actors, main interactions, decision points, and the relevant components involved in the account management service.

```plantuml
@startuml
actor EndUser as user
participant "AccountController" as controller
participant "AccountService" as service
participant "Feign Client\n(Validation Service)" as validationService
participant "PostgreSQL Database" as postgresDB
participant "MongoDB" as mongoDB
participant "Kafka" as kafka
participant "RabbitMQ" as rabbitMQ
participant "AccountManagerMapper" as mapper

== Account Creation ==
user -> controller : POST /accounts\n(Account object)
controller -> service : createAccount(Account object)
service -> postgresDB : checkAccountExists(ID)
alt Account exists
    service -> controller : BadRequestException
else Account does not exist
    service -> validationService : validateAccount(Account object)
    alt Account is valid
        service -> postgresDB : saveAccount(Account object)
        service -> mapper : mapToEntity(Account object)
        service -> kafka : publishAccountCreatedEvent(Account object)
        service -> rabbitMQ : publishAccountCreatedNotification(Account object)
        service -> controller : 201 Created
    else Account is invalid
        service -> controller : BadRequestException
    end
end

== Account Retrieval ==
user -> controller : GET /accounts
controller -> service : getAllAccounts()
service -> postgresDB : fetchAllAccounts()
service -> controller : return Account list

user -> controller : GET /accounts/{id}
controller -> service : getAccountById(ID)
service -> postgresDB : findAccountById(ID)
alt Account found
    service -> controller : return Account
else Account not found
    service -> controller : 404 Not Found
end

== Account Update ==
user -> controller : PUT /accounts/{id}\n(Account object)
controller -> service : updateAccount(ID, Account object)
service -> postgresDB : checkAccountExists(ID)
alt Account exists
    service -> validationService : validateAccount(Account object)
    alt Account is valid
        service -> postgresDB : updateAccount(ID, Account object)
        service -> kafka : publishAccountUpdatedEvent(Account object)
        service -> rabbitMQ : publishAccountUpdatedNotification(Account object)
        service -> controller : 200 OK
    else Account is invalid
        service -> controller : BadRequestException
    end
else Account not found
    service -> controller : ResourceNotFoundException
end

== Account Deletion ==
user -> controller : DELETE /accounts/{id}
controller -> service : deleteAccount(ID)
service -> postgresDB : checkAccountExists(ID)
alt Account exists
    service -> postgresDB : deleteAccount(ID)
    service -> kafka : publishAccountDeletedEvent(ID)
    service -> rabbitMQ : publishAccountDeletedNotification(ID)
    service -> controller : 204 No Content
else Account not found
    service -> controller : 404 Not Found
end

@enduml
```

### Explanation of the Diagram:
1. **Actors and Participants**: The diagram includes all key actors such as the End User, Account Controller, Account Service, external validation service, databases, and messaging systems (Kafka and RabbitMQ).
  
2. **Main Interactions**: Each section corresponds to a major account management operation (creation, retrieval, update, deletion) and outlines the flow of requests and responses between the components.

3. **Critical Decision Points**: The diagram highlights decision points such as checking for account existence, validating account attributes, and handling exceptions.

4. **Messages**: Clear and descriptive messages are used to indicate the actions being taken and responses being returned.

5. **Endpoints Displayed**: Each endpoint is represented in the sequence of interactions, ensuring that all functionalities are covered.

This script can be rendered using PlantUML to visualize the sequence diagram.

### Endpoint: `/accounts`

#### 1. API Specification
- **Endpoint URL**: `/accounts`
- **HTTP Method**: GET
- **Authentication & Authorization Requirements**: None
- **Description of the API Functionality**: Retrieve all accounts.

#### 2. Request Parameters
| Parameter | Type   | Required | Constraints |
|-----------|--------|----------|-------------|
| None      |        |          |             |

#### 3. Sample Request
```http
GET /accounts HTTP/1.1
Host: api.example.com
```

#### 4. Response Parameters
| Field       | Type       | Description                     |
|-------------|------------|---------------------------------|
| accounts    | Array      | List of account objects         |
| id          | String     | Unique identifier for account   |
| name        | String     | Name of the account holder      |
| email       | String     | Email associated with the account|
| accountNumber| String    | Account number                  |
| accountType | String     | Type of account (e.g., savings) |
| dob         | Date       | Date of birth of account holder  |
| bankCode    | String     | Code of the associated bank      |

#### 5. Sample Response
```json
{
  "accounts": [
    {
      "id": "1",
      "name": "John Doe",
      "email": "john.doe@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "123456789",
      "accountType": "savings",
      "dob": "1990-01-01",
      "bankCode": "XYZ123"
    },
    {
      "id": "2",
      "name": "Jane Smith",
      "email": "jane.smith@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "987654321",
      "accountType": "checking",
      "dob": "1985-05-05",
      "bankCode": "ABC456"
    }
  ]
}
```

#### 6. Components Involved
- **AccountController**
- **AccountService**
- **PostgreSQL Database**

#### 7. Data Mapping
| Source Entity       | Target Entity      | Relationship                       |
|---------------------|--------------------|------------------------------------|
| AccountEntity       | Account            | One-to-One mapping                 |

#### 8. Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "404",
    "message": "Not Found",
    "description": "No accounts found."
  }
}
```

#### 9. Root Exception Details
| Name                   | Description                       | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory | Notes         |
|------------------------|-----------------------------------|----------------|--------|-----------|---------------|
| ResourceNotFoundException | No accounts available            | None           | Error  | Optional  | Thrown when there are no accounts |

#### 10. Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message                 | Description                           |
|-----------|-------------------------|---------------------------------------|
| 404       | Not Found               | No accounts found.                   |
